# Digital Spy

**Digital Spy** (**DS**) is a British-based entertainment, television, and film website and brand, renowned for its comprehensive coverage of entertainment news, reviews, and editorial content. As the largest digital property under [Hearst UK](/Hearst_UK), Digital Spy has established itself as a leading authority in entertainment journalism since its inception in 1999. The platform caters to a global audience, offering breaking news, in-depth features, reviews, and editorial explainers, alongside its iconic [Forum](/Internet_forum), which has been a cornerstone of its community engagement.

## History

### digiNEWS (1999)

The origins of Digital Spy trace back to early January 1999, when Iain Chapman launched the **digiNEWS** website. This platform was dedicated to providing news, rumors, and information on [Sky](/Sky_(UK_and_Ireland))'s newly launched digital satellite platform, [SkyDigital](/Sky_(UK_and_Ireland)). Simultaneously, Chris Butcher introduced the **ONfaq** website, which offered similar content focused on the UK's digital terrestrial platform, [ONdigital](/ITV_Digital). Both sites quickly gained popularity among visitors eager for updates on these emerging TV platforms.

Recognizing the potential for collaboration, Chapman and Butcher discussed merging their sites to create the **digiNEWS Network**. This vision materialized on **28 February 1999**, when digiNEWS and ONfaq officially merged and were rebranded under the new network. The network expanded to include additional websites, such as Chris Norris's **cablenews:uk** (covering NTL and TeleWest cable services), Mark Hughes' **DVDNews** (focusing on DVD news and reviews), and Neil Wilkes' **TV:uk** (dedicated to TV news and gossip). Despite the network's growth, it initially operated from personal webspace provided by ISPs like Freeserve. Efforts soon began to integrate these diverse sites into a unified portal, laying the groundwork for what would become Digital Spy.

### Digital Spy (2000–2011)

The **Digital Spy forums** made their debut on **1 March 2000**, built on the UBB forum platform. This marked a significant step in fostering community interaction and discussion. The newly christened **Digital Spy news portal** went live on **19 May 2001**, powered by a custom-built content management system known as **RAMS** (Remote Article Management System).

In late 2001, **Digital Spy Limited** was formally incorporated by Alan Jay, Neil Wilkes, and Mark Hughes, with Iain Chapman, Jose Cardoso, and James Welsh later joining as shareholders. This corporate structure provided a solid foundation for the platform's continued growth and development.

A pivotal moment in Digital Spy's history occurred on **9 April 2008**, when it was announced that the website had been acquired by magazine publisher [Hachette Filipacchi UK](/Hachette_Filipacchi_M%C3%A9dias), a subsidiary of the [Lagardère Group](/Lagard%C3%A8re_Group), for a "significant" sum. This acquisition underscored the platform's value and potential in the digital media landscape.

In **March 2011**, former [NME.com](/NME) and [FHM.com](/FHM) editor **David Moynihan** succeeded Neil Wilkes as Editor, bringing fresh perspectives and editorial direction to the platform.

### Digital Spy at Hearst (2011–present)

On **1 August 2011**, ownership of Hachette UK was transferred to **Hearst Magazines UK**, with the Digital Spy editorial team and operations remaining unaffected. This transition marked the beginning of a new era for the platform under the Hearst umbrella.

Digital Spy's commitment to excellence was recognized on **2 May 2013**, when it won the **Media Editorial Team of the Year 2013** at the British Media Awards. This accolade was followed by another prestigious award on **3 July 2014**, when Digital Spy was named **Consumer Website of the Year 2014** at the AOP Digital Publishing Awards.

In **October 2015**, Digital Spy transitioned its content management system from RAMS to **Hearst's newly developed Media OS**, enhancing its technological capabilities and streamlining its operations.

The platform continued to evolve with key editorial appointments. In **November 2015**, former [Heat](/Heat_(magazine)) editor **Julian Linley** was appointed Editor in Chief. In **November 2016**, former [T3](/T3_(magazine)) and [Gizmodo UK](/Gizmodo) editor **Matt Hill** took over as Editor.

Digital Spy's influence and reach were further solidified in **January 2017**, when it became an official partner of the [National Television Awards](/National_Television_Awards), held at [The O2 Arena](/The_O2_Arena) and broadcast live on [ITV](/ITV_(TV_network)).

The platform's achievements continued to accumulate. In **October 2017**, Digital Spy won the **PPA Digital Content Team of the Year** award and was shortlisted for **Website of the Year** and **Content Team Leader of the Year**. In **December 2017**, nearly one million people participated in the **DS Reader Awards**, showcasing the platform's engaged and passionate community. In **March 2018**, Digital Spy was shortlisted for **International Website of the Year** at the Hearst Editorial Excellence Awards.

In **October 2018**, Digital Spy won the **PPA Digital Content Team of the Year** award for the second consecutive year, further cementing its reputation as a leader in digital entertainment journalism.

On **22 March 2021**, Digital Spy announced a significant shift in its community strategy. The platform decided to close its non-entertainment related discussion forums, such as Politics and General Discussion, while retaining those focused on Film, Entertainment, and Television. This decision was made to refocus the website's offerings and align with its core entertainment mission. The closure was implemented suddenly, within 24 hours of the announcement, which took many of its subscribed members by surprise and led to some disappointment within the community.

## Digital Spy Awards

Digital Spy has a rich history of celebrating excellence in entertainment through its awards. In **2008**, the website held its inaugural **Digital Spy Soap Awards**, with nominations curated by Digital Spy's soaps editor, Kris Green. From **2014**, the awards evolved into the annual **Digital Spy Reader Awards**, which poll the site's readers to determine the best moments in various categories.

